		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2024 SI"></a><br><code>sle2024s/paper05</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>A language-parametric test coverage framework for executable domain-specific languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/FaezehKhorram.html">Faezeh Khorram</a>, <a href="../profile/ErwanBousse.html">Erwan Bousse</a>, <a href="../profile/AntonioGarmendía.html">Antonio Garmendía</a>, <a href="../profile/JeanMarieMottu.html">Jean-Marie Mottu</a>, <a href="../profile/GersonSunyé.html">Gerson Sunyé</a>, <a href="../profile/ManuelWimmer.html">Manuel Wimmer</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jss.2024.111977">10.1016/j.jss.2024.111977</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The main contribution is a generic test coverage framework/metrics (model element & branch coverage) for testing executable DSL models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The approach is designed specifically for executable domain-specific languages (xDSLs) and their models/traces.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It is implemented in/for a language & modeling workbench setting (Eclipse GEMOC Studio) with a dedicated coverage rule language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The paper evaluates the framework across multiple xDSLs, models, test suites, and fault-localization scenarios.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
